  "texts": [
    "This might be just another way of making the argument set out in (§4.2): (A) supplied with the right qualification is the only thing the agent does, and (B)-(E) is just what happens, described in a way that elucidates the rationalising context for this act.",
    "But we can also turn the point around.",
    "Although the series (A)-(E) depends on an underlying causal order, and the man in acting this way expresses his understanding of a rational order in the unfolding events, none of the items mentioned is itself a non-agential event.",
    "Although, as Davidson notes, the descriptions of the form 'the event that happens when someone φ-s' are trivial given the description 'S φ-s', this triviality depends on the action description's being given.",
    "The event descriptions constructed by putting (A)-(E) in the passive voice are conceptually dependent on the action description."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}